PISA 2012 Test Data Exploration: A Focus on Family-based Factors¶

by Yan LU¶

Investigation Overview¶

In this study, I wanted to look at the effects of family-based factors on the students' academic performance. The factors to be investigated are: language at home, household possessions, family status, parents' working status, and parents' education levels. We are also interested to see if the effects identified are valid across countries.

Dataset Overview¶

Around 510,000 students in 65 economies took part in the PISA 2012 assessment of reading, mathematics and science representing about 28 million 15-year-olds globally. Of those economies, 44 took part in an assessment of creative problem solving and 18 in an assessment of financial literacy. The provided dataset consisted of 485490 observations with 636 variables.

# convert 'Family_status', 'Books_at_home', 'Edu_level_mother', 'Edu_level_father', 'Highest_edu_level_parents' 
# 'Mother_job', 'Father_job' into ordered categorical types
ordinal_var_dict = {'Family_status': ['Live with both', 'Live with mother', 'Live with father', 'Live with none'],
                    'Books_at_home': ['0-10 books', '11-25 books', '26-100 books', '101-200 books', '201-500 books', 
                                      'More than 500 books'],
                    'Edu_level_mother': ['None','ISCED 1','ISCED 2','ISCED 3B, C', 'ISCED 3A, ISCED 4','ISCED 5A, 6'],
                    'Edu_level_father': ['None','ISCED 1','ISCED 2','ISCED 3B, C', 'ISCED 3A, ISCED 4','ISCED 5A, 6'],
                    'Highest_edu_level_parents': ['None','ISCED 1','ISCED 2','ISCED 3B, C', 'ISCED 3A, ISCED 4','ISCED 5A, 6'],
                    'Mother_job': ['Working full-time <for pay>', 'Working part-time <for pay>', 
                                   'Not working, but looking for a job', 'Other (e.g. home duties, retired)'],
                    'Father_job': ['Working full-time <for pay>', 'Working part-time <for pay>', 
                                   'Not working, but looking for a job', 'Other (e.g. home duties, retired)']}

for var in ordinal_var_dict:
    ordered_var = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = ordinal_var_dict[var])
    pisa_home_clean[var] = pisa_home_clean[var].astype(ordered_var)

Distribution of Scores across Countries¶

  • Most countries ranking from 10th to 40th seem to perform comparably to each other.
  • Top players outperform significantly over the other countries.
  • The outliers of each subject come from different countries.
In [40]:
plt.figure(figsize = [15,12])

Language at Home vs. Scores¶

Language at home is supposed to influence the test score as students who speak the same language as test language is likely to perform better than students who speak a different language. However, the violin plot shows no significant difference between these two categories.

Family Status vs. Scores¶

In this study, we define the family status as whether the participants live in a two-parents family, one parents family (live with mother only/live with father only), or no parents family. We are interested to see if the family status is an important predictors of academic achievement.

Parents Employment Status vs. Score¶

Students with fully employed parents do better in tests. Having a mother who works part-time or full-time is associated with test outcomes. Students with a father employed less than full-time have lower test scores than if the father had a full-time postion. A stay-at-home (Other) parent does not improve scores. It will be interesting to see if the finding is consistent across different countries.

Parents Education Level vs. Scores¶

Students with higher educated parents do better in tests. Students with one or two parents whose whose education level equal or higher than ISCED 5A,6 have the highest scores. The difference between ISCED 3B,C and ISCED 3A,4 is not significant.

Plot Matrices of Math_score, Reading_score, and Science_score¶

There is a strong positive correlation between each pair of the three variables. Therefore, for the following two multivariate analysis, we will only plot the visualizations using Math_score.

In [59]:
grid = sb.pairplot(data = pisa_home_clean, vars=["Math_score", "Reading_score", "Science_score"]);
grid.fig.suptitle("Pair-by-pair representation of different scores' correlation",  y = 1.02 , fontsize = 'x-large');

Math Score by Family Status and Country¶

Students in homes with two parents do better in all three subjects. Exceptions can be observed for Montenegro, Peru, and Vietnam. As observed in bivariate exploration, students with neither parent living at home have the lowest achievement in most countries, except for Estonia, Hong Kong-China, Jordan, Japan, Singapore, Tunisia. The reasons can be explored in future study by taking into account other variables.

In [61]:
g = sb.FacetGrid(data = pisa_home_clean, col = 'Country', col_wrap = 8)
g.map(sb.boxplot, 'Math_score', 'Family_status')
g.fig.suptitle("Math Score by Family Status and Country", y = 1.02 , fontsize = 'xx-large');

Math Score by Parent Employment Status and Country¶

Parent employment status is also an important predictor of academic achievement. The pointplots of math score on this categorical variable across countries indicate that in most countries, students with fully employed fathers do best in tests, while students with fathers who is not working but looking for a job score lowest. Having a mother who works part-time or full-time is associated with high scores, while a stay-at-home (Other) parent does not improve scores. An exception can be observed from Liechtenstein, ranking 6th in math test. In Liechtenstein, the highest scores come from students with non-working mothers or part-time working fathers. Further exploration is required to find out the reason.

In [67]:
grouped = pisa_home_clean.groupby('Country')['Math_score'].mean()
country_ordered = grouped.sort_values(ascending=False)
country_index= country_ordered.index

plt.figure(figsize = [10,10])
plt.suptitle('Math Score by Parent Employment Status and Country', y = 0.92 , fontsize = 'xx-large')

                  pallete = 'mako', ci = None, order = country_index, scale = 0.6)
